{{About||the sport|dog agility|the agile in computer software|agile software development|use in business|business agility|global logistics company|Agility Logistics}}
[[File:Matten13.jpg|thumb|300px|Material to exercise the balance agility for children]]
'''Agility''' or ''nimbleness'' is the ability to  change the body's [[list of human positions|position]] efficiently, and requires the integration of isolated movement skills using a combination of [[balance (ability)|balance]], [[coordination (physiology)|coordination]], [[speed]], [[reflexes]], [[physical strength|strength]], and [[endurance]]. Agility is the ability to change the direction of the body in an efficient and effective manner and to achieve this requires a combination of
* balance – the ability to maintain equilibrium when stationary or moving (i.e. not to fall over) through the coordinated actions of our sensory functions (eyes, ears and the proprioceptive organs in our joints);
* static balance – the ability to retain the centre of mass above the base of support in a stationary position;
* dynamic balance – the ability to maintain balance with body movement;
* speed - the ability to move all or part of the body quickly;
* strength - the ability of a muscle or muscle group to overcome a resistance; and lastly,
* coordination – the ability to control the movement of the body in co-operation with the body's sensory functions (e.g., in catching a ball [ball, hand, and eye coordination]).

In sports, agility is often defined in terms of an individual sport, due to it being an integration of many components each used differently (specific to all of sorts of different sports). Sheppard and Young (2006) defined agility as a "rapid whole body movement with change of velocity or direction in response to a stimulus".<ref>{{citation |title=Agility literature review: classifications, training and testing |author1=J. M. Sheppard |author2=WB Young |journal=Journal of Sports Sciences |date=September 2006 |volume=24 |issue=9 |pages=919-932}}</ref>

Agility is also an important attribute in many [[role playing games]], both video games such as [[Pokémon (video game series)|Pokémon]], and tabletop games such as ''[[Dungeons & Dragons]]''. Agility may affect the character's ability to evade an enemy's attack or land their own, or pickpocket and pick locks.

