The '''Lou Gehrig Memorial Award''' is given annually to a [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) player who best exhibits the character and integrity of [[Lou Gehrig]], both [[Sportsmanship|on the field]] and off it.<ref name=PDT>{{cite web|title=The Lou Gehrig Memorial Award|url=http://www.phideltatheta.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=27|accessdate=November 6, 2012|publisher=Phi Delta Theta International Site}}</ref> The award was created by the [[Phi Delta Theta]] fraternity in honor of Gehrig, who was a member of the fraternity at [[Columbia University]]. It was first presented in {{baseball year|1955}}, fourteen years after Gehrig's death. The award's purpose is to recognize a player's exemplary contributions in "both his community and philanthropy."<ref name=PDT/>  The bestowal of the award is overseen by the headquarters of the Phi Delta Theta in [[Oxford, Ohio]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ceeU7xSLw5kC&pg=PA518&lpg=PA518&dq=lou+gehrig+memorial+award#v=onepage&q=lou%20gehrig%20memorial%20award&f=false|title=The Dickson Baseball Dictionary|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|date=June 13, 2011|last=Dickson|first=Paul|pages=518|accessdate=November 9, 2012|isbn=9780393073492}}</ref> and the name of each winner is inscribed onto the Lou Gehrig Award plaque in the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] in [[Cooperstown, New York]]. It is the only MLB award conferred by a [[fraternity]].<ref name=PDT/>

Twenty-four winners of the Lou Gehrig Memorial Award are members of the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|National Baseball Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/hof.shtml|title=Baseball Hall of Fame Inductees|work=Baseball-Reference.com|publisher=Sports Reference LLC|accessdate=November 9, 2012}}</ref>  The inaugural winner was [[Alvin Dark]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Gehrig Award Is Given To Dark|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=1nIuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=K4AFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4368,961054&dq=alvin+dark+lou+gehrig+memorial+award&hl=en|date=January 9, 1956|page=18|accessdate=January 15, 2013|newspaper=The Modesto Bee|agency=United Press International}}{{dead link|date=October 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Curt Schilling]] (1995) and [[Shane Victorino]] (2008) received the award for working with the [[ALS Association]] and raising money for [[amyotrophic lateral sclerosis]] (ALS). The disease took Gehrig's life and is eponymously known as "Lou Gehrig's disease".<ref>{{cite news|title=Schilling gets Gehrig Award|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=xosxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jaYFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1184,1201648&dq=schilling+lou+gehrig+memorial+award&hl=en|date=January 4, 1996|page=C5|accessdate=January 15, 2013|newspaper=Reading Eagle}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Phillies' Shane Victorino Wins Phi Delta Theta's Lou Gehrig Award|url=http://www.phideltatheta.org/content/view/683/132/|accessdate=January 16, 2013|publisher=Phi Delta Theta International Site|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805132040/http://www.phideltatheta.org/content/view/683/132/|archivedate=August 5, 2012|df=}}</ref>  [[Mike Timlin]] won the award in 2007 for his efforts in raising awareness and finding a cure for ALS, which took his mother's life in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mike Timlin&nbsp;– Boston Red Sox|url=http://www.phideltatheta.org/content/view/676/132/|accessdate=January 15, 2013|publisher=Phi Delta Theta International Site|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805131845/http://www.phideltatheta.org/content/view/676/132/|archivedate=August 5, 2012|df=}}</ref>

Winners of the Lou Gehrig Memorial Award have undertaken a variety of different causes. Many winners, including [[Rick Sutcliffe]],<ref name=Sutcliffe>{{cite news|title=Cubs Sutcliffe an ace on and off the field|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=qVgvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9doFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1210,5092578&dq=lou+gehrig+memorial+award&hl=en|first=Bob|last=Verdi|date=December 27, 1987|page=C12|accessdate=November 14, 2012|newspaper=The Beaver County Times}}</ref> [[Barry Larkin]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Larkin will receive Lou Gehrig Award|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:CNPB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0EB031C7592DDFB3&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggdocs&req_dat=105B9A93AF33E3E3|date=January 25, 1995|accessdate=January 15, 2013|page=4B|newspaper=The Cincinnati Post}} '''{{subscription required}}</ref> [[Mark McGwire]],<ref>{{cite news|title=McGwire Wins Gehrig Memorial Award|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:APNS&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=14168D976A4CE350&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggdocs&req_dat=105B9A93AF33E3E3|date=March 17, 2000|accessdate=January 15, 2013|agency=Associated Press}} '''{{subscription required}}</ref> [[Todd Stottlemyre]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Pitcher Todd Stottlemyre wins the Lou Gehrig Memorial award|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=1gJPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Th8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6748,1488074&dq=lou+gehrig+memorial+award&hl=en|date=September 19, 2001|page=9|accessdate=January 15, 2013|newspaper=Star-News|location=Wilmington}}</ref> and [[Derek Jeter]],<ref name=Jeter>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlb.com/players/jeter_derek/turn2/index.jsp|title=Turn 2 Foundation Mission Statement|accessdate=November 6, 2012|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media}}</ref> worked with children in need. Jeter assisted children and teenagers in avoiding [[drug addiction|drug]] and [[alcoholism|alcohol addiction]]<ref name=Jeter/> through his [[Turn&nbsp;2&nbsp;Foundation]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeter honored with Lou Gehrig Memorial Award|url=http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120118&content_id=26386450&vkey=news_nyy&c_id=nyy|date=January 18, 2012|accessdate=November 6, 2012|first=Adam|last=Berry|work=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010213932/http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120118&content_id=26386450&vkey=news_nyy&c_id=nyy|archivedate=October 10, 2012|df=}}</ref> while Sutcliffe visited disabled children in hospitals<ref name=Sutcliffe/> and bestowed college scholarships to underprivileged juveniles through his foundation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sutcliffe given Gehrig Memorial Award|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=8IZGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=0jMNAAAAIBAJ&pg=5406,2792141&dq=lou+gehrig+memorial+award&hl=en|date=November 24, 1987|page=2B|accessdate=November 14, 2012|newspaper=The Evening News|location=Newburgh|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>  Other winners devoted their work to aiding individuals who had a specific illness, such as [[Albert Pujols]], whose daughter suffers from [[Down syndrome]], and who devoted the [[Albert Pujols#Pujols Family Foundation|Pujols Family Foundation]] to helping those with the disorder,<ref>{{cite web|title=Albert Pujols Wins Phi Delta Theta's Lou Gehrig Award|url=http://www.phideltatheta.org/content/view/1216/132/|accessdate=January 15, 2013|publisher=Phi Delta Theta International Site|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120805131924/http://www.phideltatheta.org/content/view/1216/132/|archivedate=August 5, 2012|df=}}</ref> and [[Ryan Zimmerman]], who established the ziMS Foundation to raise money for [[multiple sclerosis]], the disease which afflicts his mother.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ryan Zimmerman to be presented with the Lou Gehrig Memorial Award|url=http://zimsfoundation.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/06-25-12-Zimmerman-Receives-Gehrig-Award-1.pdf|date=June 25, 2012|accessdate=January 16, 2012|work=ziMS Foundation|publisher=Washington Nationals}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/nationals-journal/post/ryan-zimmerman-honored-for-his-charitable-work-with-the-lou-gehrig-memorial-award/2012/06/25/gJQAvISD2V_blog.html|title=Ryan Zimmerman honored for his charitable work with the Lou Gehrig Memorial Award|first=James|last=Wagner|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=June 25, 2012|accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>

